==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Referendary
<hw>Ref`er*en"da*ry</hw> <pr>(r?f`?r*?n"d?*r?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[LL. <ets>referendarius</ets>, fr. L. <ets>referendus</ets> to be
referred, gerundive of <ets>referre</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧f⟦eacute⟧rendaire</ets>. See <er>Refer</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One to whose decision a cause is referred; a
referee.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An officer who delivered the royal answer to
petitions.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Referendaries</xex>, or masters of
request.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Harmar.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Formerly, an officer of state charged with the duty
of procuring and dispatching diplomas and decrees.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Referendum</ent>⟦br⟧
